Level Difficulty: Medium
Commands Used: cat,whoami,echo,md5sum,cut,bash
              cat -> reads and prints file content
              whoami -> prints the current username
              echo -> prints text, used here to build a string before hashing it
              md5sum -> computes the md5 hash of whatever input it receives
              cut -> extracts a specific field from text, -d sets the delimiter, -f picks which field
              bash -> explicitly runs a script with bash, used here to execute the script ourselves instead of just reading it
Steps: cd /etc/cron.d && cat cronjob_bandit23 [confirms this cron job runs /usr/bin/cronjob_bandit23.sh every minute, as bandit23]
       cat /usr/bin/cronjob_bandit23.sh [reads the script - it grabs whoami, builds a filename by md5 hashing the string "I am user <name>", then copies that user's password file to /tmp/<that hash>]
       bash /usr/bin/cronjob_bandit23.sh [ran the script ourselves as bandit22 ]
       echo I am user bandit23 | md5sum | cut -d ' ' -f 1 [manually computes the same hash the script would produce, but for bandit23 instead of ourselves - since the real cron job runs this script every minute AS bandit23, that file already exists in /tmp with bandit23's password in it]
       cat /tmp/<that hash> [reads the file, gets bandit23's password]

Note: cat-ing the script only shows its text, it doesnt run it or import its variables into our shell.
